The above example is an example of tight coupling. When you modify the class A. It will directly affect B.

Consider the class 
```
public interface Vehicle {
     int calculateSpeed();
}
public class Car implements Vehicle {
     public int calculateSpeed() {
          return 100;
     }
}
public class Bike implements Vehicle {
     public int calculateSpeed() {
          return 50;
     }
}
public class Speedometer {

     private Vehicle h;
     //getter and setter of h
}

public int speedCalculator() {
     return h.calculateSpeed();
}
}
```
This speedometer class is loosely coupled as the changes in Bike or Car does not impact directly. You can also inject Train class to Speedometer class. It all depends on the bean injection.

